    "summary": "The Oracle at Delphi (active c. 800–390 BC, at its most influential in 500–300 BC) was the most prestigious religious oracle in the ancient Greek world, housed in the sanctuary of Apollo on the slopes of Mount Parnassus, whose pronouncements — delivered by a priestess (Pythia) in a state of trance-like inspiration — influenced the decisions of cities, kings, and generals across the Mediterranean world.\n\nConsultants traveled from across the Greek world and beyond (including Lydian king Croesus and Athenians during the [[event:1001|Greco-Persian Wars]]) to ask the Pythia questions on matters ranging from colonization to war to personal affairs. The Pythia's utterances, often cryptic and ambiguous, were interpreted by priest-interpreters and rendered into formal responses. Famous responses include the oracle to Croesus that 'if he crosses the Halys River, a great empire will be destroyed' (it was his own), and the response to Athens during Xerxes' invasion to trust in the 'wooden walls' (interpreted as ships, leading to the [[event:1005|Battle of Salamis]] strategy). Geological research has revealed traces of ethylene gas in a fault beneath the temple, possibly inducing the Pythia's altered state. The sanctuary also hosted the Pythian Games (second in prestige only to the Olympics), housed a treasury of offerings from across the Greek world, and served as a common ground for inter-state relations.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythia",
